# Import necessary libraries
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import json

# Import the AppStore class from the app_store_scraper module
from app_store_scraper import AppStore
# Create an instance of the AppStore class for the Tinder app
tinder = AppStore(country='us', app_name='tinder-dating-chat-friends', app_id='547702041')

# Scrape the app reviews with a delay of 1 second between requests
tinder.review(sleep=1)

# Convert the list of reviews into a DataFrame with one column named 'review'
tinderdf = pd.DataFrame(np.array(tinder.reviews),columns=['review'])
# Split the dictionary in the 'review' column into separate columns and join with the original DataFrame
# The 'pop' method removes the 'review' column and converts the dictionaries to a list of rows
tinderdf2 = tinderdf.join(pd.DataFrame(tinderdf.pop('review').tolist()))
# Display the first 5 rows of the final DataFrame
tinderdf2.head()

In [ ]:
# Import Sort and reviews functions from google_play_scraper
from google_play_scraper import Sort, reviews

# Fetch 3 of the newest 5-star reviews for the Tinder app
result, continuation_token = reviews(
    'com.tinder',
    lang='en',
    country='us',
    sort=Sort.NEWEST,
    count=3,
    filter_score_with=5
)
# Fetch the next batch of reviews using the continuation token
result, _ = reviews(
    'com.tinder',
    continuation_token=continuation_token
)
In [ ]:
# Import Sort and reviews_all to fetch all reviews
from google_play_scraper import Sort, reviews_all
# Fetch all reviews for the Tinder app without filtering
result = reviews_all(
    'com.tinder',
    sleep_milliseconds=0,
    lang='en',
    country='us',
)
In [ ]:
# Convert the list of Google Play reviews (stored in 'result') into a DataFrame with one column labeled 'review'
tinderdfg = pd.DataFrame(np.array(result),columns=['review'])
# Extract the dictionary content from the 'review' column and expand it into separate columns
# 'pop' removes the 'review' column and 'tolist()' converts it into a list of dictionaries for DataFrame conversion
tinderdfg2 = tinderdfg.join(pd.DataFrame(tinderdfg.pop('review').tolist()))
# Display the first 5 rows of the final DataFrame with structured review data
tinderdfg2.head()

# Install the necessary libraries
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from wordcloud import WordCloud

# Load the datasets
google_reviews_path = 'tinder_google_play_reviews.csv'
apple_reviews_path = 'tinder-apple-reviews.csv'
feature_timeline_path = 'Timeline.csv'

# Load the CSV files into DataFrames
google_df = pd.read_csv(google_reviews_path)
apple_df = pd.read_csv(apple_reviews_path)
feature_df = pd.read_csv(feature_timeline_path)

# Display the first few rows of the data to inspect the structure
print(google_df.head())
print(apple_df.head())
print(feature_df.head())

# Plot 1: Sentiment Distribution from Google Play Reviews (or Apple)
google_df['sentiment'] = google_df['score'].apply(lambda x: 'Positive' if x >= 4 else ('Neutral' if x == 3 else 'Negative'))

# Sentiment distribution plot for Google Play
sentiment_dist_google = google_df['sentiment'].value_counts()

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.barplot(x=sentiment_dist_google.index, y=sentiment_dist_google.values, palette="Blues_d")
plt.title("Sentiment Distribution in Google Play Reviews")
plt.xlabel("Sentiment")
plt.ylabel("Number of Reviews")
plt.show()

# Plot 2: Reviews Count by Platform (Google Play vs Apple)
google_df['platform'] = 'Google Play Store'
apple_df['platform'] = 'Apple App Store'

# Combine both dataframes
combined_reviews = pd.concat([google_df[['content', 'platform']], apple_df[['review', 'platform']]])

# Count the number of reviews by platform
reviews_by_platform = combined_reviews['platform'].value_counts()

# Plot the reviews count by platform
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
sns.barplot(x=reviews_by_platform.index, y=reviews_by_platform.values, palette="Set2")
plt.title("Comparing Google Play and Apple Review Count")
plt.xlabel("Platform")
plt.ylabel("Number of Reviews")
plt.show()

# Plot 3: Timeline of Feature Releases
feature_df['ReleaseDate'] = pd.to_datetime(feature_df['ReleaseDate'], errors='coerce')

# Plotting the timeline of feature releases
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.countplot(data=feature_df, x=feature_df['ReleaseDate'].dt.year, palette="muted")
plt.title("Feature Releases Over Time")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Number of Features Released")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

# Plot 4: Word Cloud of Frequent Terms in Reviews
# Combine all review content (from both Google and Apple) into one text blob
combined_reviews_text = ' '.join(google_df['content'].dropna()) + ' ' + ' '.join(apple_df['review'].dropna())

# Generate a word cloud
wordcloud = WordCloud(width=800, height=400, background_color='white').generate(combined_reviews_text)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation='bilinear')
plt.axis('off')
plt.title("Frequent Terms in Reviews")
plt.show()

# Plot 7: Average Rating Over Time
google_df['at'] = pd.to_datetime(google_df['at'], errors='coerce')
google_df.set_index('at', inplace=True)

# Resampling to monthly average rating
avg_rating_google = google_df['score'].resample('M').mean()

# Plotting average rating over time for Google Play
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
avg_rating_google.plot(color='red')
plt.title("Average Rating Over Time (Google Play Store)")
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Average Rating")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()
